Pima Indians Diabetes - Data Exploration

The Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset involves predicting the onset of diabetes within 5 years in Pima Indians given medical details. It is a binary(2 - class) classification problem.

The number of observations for each class is not balanced.

There are 768 observations with 8 input variables and 1 output variable. Missing values are believed to be encoded with zero values. The variable names are as follows:

  1. Number of times pregnant.
  2. Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test.
  3. Diastolic blood pressure(mm Hg) .
  4. Triceps skinfold thickness(mm) .
  5. 2 - Hour serum insulin(mu U / ml) .
  6. Body mass index(weight in kg / (height in m) ^ 2) .
  7. Diabetes pedigree function.
  8. Age(years) .
  9. Class variable(0 or 1) .

The baseline performance of predicting the most prevalent class is a classification accuracy of approximately 65%.

Top results achieve a classification accuracy of approximately 77%.
